  "prompt": "For NSF Fellowship applicants, what is the difference between \"Very Good\" and \"Excellent\"?",
  "response": "The National Science Foundation (NSF) Graduate Research Fellowship Program (GRFP) uses specific criteria to evaluate applicants, typically involving ratings such as \"Very Good\" and \"Excellent\". While the exact criteria can vary slightly depending on the specific reviewers and fields of study, here are general distinctions between these two ratings:\n\n1. **Excellent**:\n   - **Intellectual Merit**: The applicant demonstrates outstanding academic performance and research potential. This includes a strong record of publications, presentations, and awards. Their research proposal is exceptionally well thought out, innovative, and feasible.\n   - **Broader Impacts**: The applicant shows exceptional ability to communicate the significance and broader impacts of their work. They have a clear plan for how their research will benefit society and contribute to scientific advancement. They have also demonstrated a commitment to outreach, education, and community involvement.\n\n2. **Very Good**:\n   - **Intellectual Merit**: The applicant has a strong academic background and demonstrates good research potential. They may have fewer publications, presentations, or awards compared to those rated \"Excellent\". Their research proposal is solid but may lack the same level of innovation or feasibility.\n   - **Broader Impacts**: The applicant communicates the importance of their research but with less clarity or convincing detail than those rated \"Excellent\". They have some evidence of outreach or community involvement, but it is not as extensive or impactful.\n\nIn summary, \"Excellent\" applicants are those who stand out in both intellectual merit and broader impacts, demonstrating exceptional capabilities and potential for significant contributions to their field and society. \"Very Good\" applicants are strong candidates, but may not have the same level of achievements or clarity in their proposals and impact plans.",
